messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Analysis summary:
- This AdminController defines four REST endpoints via Spring's @RequestMapping with explicit literal paths.
- All four endpoints are standard RESTful HTTP actions (GET or POST) and are implemented as methods in this same AdminController class.
- Each path is a literal string in the source, no path parameters are used, and there are no path prefixes in these mappings.
- The endpoints appear to be for admin operations and data seeding, not for unit/functional testing themselves.

API entries extracted from AdminController.java:

[
  {
    "path": "/admin/printshops",
    "handler": "AdminController#getPrinShopsList",
    "inSameFile": true,
    "pathIsPrefix": false,
    "pathFromLiteral": true,
    "pathFromNamingConvention": false,
    "isREST": true,
    "isTesting": false
  },
  {
    "path": "/admin/register",
    "handler": "AdminController#newAdmin",
    "inSameFile": true,
    "pathIsPrefix": false,
    "pathFromLiteral": true,
    "pathFromNamingConvention": false,
    "isREST": true,
    "isTesting": false
  },
  {
    "path": "/admin/seed",
    "handler": "AdminController#seed",
    "inSameFile": true,
    "pathIsPrefix": false,
    "pathFromLiteral": true,
    "pathFromNamingConvention": false,
    "isREST": true,
    "isTesting": false
  },
  {
    "path": "/admin/useed",
    "handler": "AdminController#useed",
    "inSameFile": true,
    "pathIsPrefix": false,
    "pathFromLiteral": true,
    "pathFromNamingConvention": false,
    "isREST": true,
    "isTesting": false
  }
]

Explanation:
- Each API entry corresponds to a method annotated with @RequestMapping in AdminController with a literal path value. There are no dynamic path segments, so path parameters are not present.
- All handlers are instance methods of the AdminController class, i.e., not anonymous implementations. Therefore, the handler field reflects the specific method, e.g., AdminController#getPrinShopsList.
- All endpoints are implemented in the same source file (AdminController.java), so inSameFile is true for all.
- None of the paths are prefixes for broader mappings; each is an explicit, full path.
- All path strings are extracted from literal strings in the source code (pathFromLiteral = true).
- The paths are not derived from naming conventions supported by the framework (pathFromNamingConvention = false).
- The API entries represent RESTful endpoints (isREST = true).
- These endpoints appear to be for admin operations and data seeding, not for testing purposes, so isTesting = false.

path.description: The HTTP request path, which must begin with a forward slash (/) and have path parameters wrapped in curly braces ({}). Set this to null if it cannot be determined.
path.title: Path

handler.description: The function, class, class method, or object that handles the HTTP request. Use exactly "anonymous" to denote an anonymous implementation.
handler.title: Handler

handler_in_same_file.description: Whether the handler's implementation is present in the same source code file, rather than being imported.
handler_in_same_file.title: Handler In Same File

path_is_prefix.description: Whether the path string is a prefix rather than a full path.
path_is_prefix.title: Path Is Prefix

path_from_string_literal.description: Whether the path string is extracted from a literal string defined in the source code.
path_from_string_literal.title: Path From String Literal

path_from_naming_convention.description: Whether the path string is derived from a naming convention supported by the framework.
path_from_naming_convention.title: Path From Naming Convention

is_restful_api.description: Whether the API entry is for a RESTful API, rather than other types of APIs.
is_restful_api.title: Is Restful Api

is_testing_purposes.description: Whether the API entry is intended for testing purposes, such as unit tests or functional tests.
is_testing_purposes.title: Is Testing Purposes

entry.description: List of API entries you found.
entry.title: Entry
